\details{
The analysis proceeds in four steps:

\strong{1. Data preparation.} The input time series is parsed via
\code{prepare_timeseries_data()}. If \code{windows} is \code{NULL}, a sequence of 8
window sizes is generated spanning from \code{max(20, n/20)} to
\code{min(n/2, 200)} on a linear grid, rounded to integers. This range
covers small windows (high temporal resolution but noisy estimates)
through large windows (smooth estimates but low resolution).

\strong{2. Detrending.} For each detrend method, the full series is
preprocessed: \code{"none"} uses the raw series; \code{"linear"} removes the
best-fit linear trend via OLS residuals. Detrending before computing
EWS metrics eliminates confounding from deterministic trends that
could inflate autocorrelation or variance artificially.

\strong{3. Rolling metric computation.} For each (window, detrend)
combination, the specified metric is computed on right-aligned rolling
windows. The available metrics are:
\itemize{
\item \code{"ar1"}: Lag-1 autocorrelation estimated via OLS AR(1).
Rising AR(1) is a classic signature of critical slowing down
(Scheffer et al., 2009).
\item \code{"sd"}: Standard deviation. Increasing variance is the
second canonical EWS indicator alongside AR(1).
\item \code{"variance"}: Variance (SD squared). Equivalent information
to SD but on the original scale, which may be preferable for
some comparisons.
\item \code{"skewness"}: Third standardized moment. Non-zero skewness
indicates asymmetric fluctuations, which can precede transitions
in systems with asymmetric potential wells.
\item \code{"kurtosis"}: Excess kurtosis (fourth standardized moment
minus 3). Heavy-tailed fluctuations (positive kurtosis) can
signal proximity to a transition.
\item \code{"cv"}: Coefficient of variation (SD / |mean|). Useful when
the mean is non-zero and relative dispersion matters more than
absolute dispersion.
